  <h2>How a bug zapper works</h2>
  <p>
    A zapper uses <strong>ultraviolet light</strong> to attract flying insects
    toward an electrified metal grid, which kills them on contact — that faint
    snap you hear on a summer evening. It's an <em>attract-and-kill</em> device
    working on a broad range of insects, and it works instantly and continuously.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Strengths:</strong> covers a lot of ground (some outdoor units are
    rated for up to an acre), needs no consumables, kills a wide variety of
    flying insects, and works from the moment you plug it in.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Limits:</strong> UV is a general insect attractant, not a
    mosquito-specific one — you'll catch moths, midges, gnats, and beetles along
    with mosquitoes. Instant-kill models make an audible snap, which some people
    dislike near a patio.
  </p>

  <h2>How a mosquito trap works</h2>
  <p>
    A trap doesn't rely mainly on light. It imitates the things a mosquito
    actually hunts — <strong>carbon dioxide, warmth, and moisture</strong> — and
    uses a quiet fan to pull them into a basket or onto a sticky board, where they
    dehydrate. It's a <em>lure-and-capture</em> device, and it's deliberately
    tuned to biting insects.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Strengths:</strong> far more targeted at mosquitoes specifically,
    completely silent, and by capturing females before they lay, it reduces the
    next generation as well as the current one.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Limits:</strong> works over days and weeks rather than instantly,
    generally covers a smaller area, and many models need replacement parts
    (sticky boards, attractant refills, or CO2).
  </p>

  <h2>The bit most articles skip</h2>
  <p>
    Mosquitoes locate you primarily by the <strong>carbon dioxide you exhale</strong>
    and your body heat — not by light. That single fact explains the whole
    category: it's why UV zappers catch enormous numbers of insects but aren't the
    most efficient mosquito tool, and why CO2-mimicking traps exist at all.
  </p>
  <p>
    It also explains why a zapper can seem to "not work" even while its tray fills
    up — it <em>is</em> killing thousands of insects, just not primarily the ones
    biting you.
  </p>

  <h2>Which should you buy?</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bedroom, nursery, or living room</strong> → a silent fan-and-sticky trap, or a chemical-free UV bulb. Nothing that snaps.</li>
    <li><strong>Covered patio or deck where you sit</strong> → a UV device is ideal: broad flying-insect control exactly where you are.</li>
    <li><strong>Large open yard, mosquitoes specifically</strong> → a CO2-style trap, run continuously through the season.</li>
    <li><strong>Gnats and fruit flies indoors</strong> → a fan-and-sticky indoor trap. This is what they're best at.</li>
    <li><strong>Whole-property problem</strong> → both: a trap working the yard's mosquito population down over weeks, plus a device on the patio for immediate comfort.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Neither is a substitute for source control</h2>
  <p>
    Whichever you buy, it's a layer on top — not the foundation. If there's still
    water breeding a fresh generation every 7–10 days in your gutters or plant
    saucers, no device keeps up with the supply. Empty the water first, treat what
    you can't empty, then let the device handle what's left. Our full walkthrough
    is in <a href="/blog/get-rid-of-mosquitoes-in-yard/">how to get rid of mosquitoes in your yard</a>.
  </p>

